[0m[49m[39m  171, 174[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  172, 175[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  173, 176[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  174, 177[0m:[39m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns relevant to this recipe:
[0m[49m[39m  175, 178[0m:[39m[49m >
[0m[49m[39m  176, 179[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration): Demonstrates Comprehend Medical entity extraction and integration with clinical data standards
[0m[49m[39m  177, 180[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-examples`](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): General SageMaker examples including NLP model training and deployment patterns
[0m[49m[39m  178, 181[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  179, 182[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  180, 183[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  181, 184[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract entities from clinical text.** The first stage identifies all clinical entities (conditions, medications, procedures, tests) in the note and returns their character positions and basic traits. Comprehend Medical's DetectEntitiesV2 handles this. It returns entities with category labels (MEDICAL_CONDITION, MEDICATION, TEST_TREATMENT_PROCEDURE) and basic traits including negation. For simple present/absent classification, this built-in negation trait may be sufficient. For the full assertion taxonomy, we use the extracted entities as input to the custom classifier in Step 3. Skip this step and you have no entities to classify. Get it wrong and assertion classification inherits the errors.
[0m[49m[39m  182, 185[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  183, 186[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  184, 187[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_entities(note_text):
[0m[49m[39m  185, 188[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the medical NLP service to find clinical entities in the text.
[0m[49m[39m  186, 189[0m:[39m[49m     // The service returns each entity with:
[0m[49m[39m  187, 190[0m:[39m[49m     //   - text: the actual words ("chest pain", "diabetes")
[0m[49m[39m  188, 191[0m:[39m[49m     //   - category: what type of entity (condition, medication, etc.)
[0m[49m[39m  189, 192[0m:[39m[49m     //   - begin_offset / end_offset: character positions in the original text
[0m[49m[39m  190, 193[0m:[39m[49m     //   - traits: basic attributes including whether negation was detected
[0m[49m[39m  191, 194[0m:[39m[49m     //   - score: confidence in the entity detection (0.0 to 1.0)
[0m[49m[39m  192, 195[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  193, 196[0m:[39m[49m     response = call MedicalNLP.DetectEntities with:
[0m[49m[39m  194, 197[0m:[39m[49m         text = note_text
[0m[49m[39m  195, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  196, 199[0m:[39m[49m     entities = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  197, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 201[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each entity in response.Entities:
[0m[49m[39m  199, 202[0m:[39m[49m         // Only keep entities with high confidence to reduce noise
[0m[49m[39m  200, 203[0m:[39m[49m         IF entity.Score >= 0.80:
[0m[49m[39m  201, 204[0m:[39m[49m             append to entities: {
[0m[49m[39m  202, 205[0m:[39m[49m                 text: entity.Text,
[0m[49m[39m  203, 206[0m:[39m[49m                 category: entity.Category,
[0m[49m[39m  204, 207[0m:[39m[49m                 begin_offset: entity.BeginOffset,
[0m[49m[39m  205, 208[0m:[39m[49m                 end_offset: entity.EndOffset,
[0m[49m[39m  206, 209[0m:[39m[49m                 traits: entity.Traits,
[0m[49m[39m  207, 210[0m:[39m[49m                 score: entity.Score
[0m[49m[39m  208, 211[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  209, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  210, 213[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN entities
[0m[49m[39m  211, 214[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  212, 215[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  213, 216[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Extract context windows for each entity.** For each extracted entity, we pull a window of surrounding text that contains the assertion-relevant cues. The context window must include enough text for the classifier to identify negation cues, hedging language, section headers, and scope boundaries, without including irrelevant text that adds noise. In practice, 2-3 sentences around the entity works well. We also prepend the section header if we can detect it, because "diabetes" in a "Family History" section means something fundamentally different than "diabetes" in "Assessment."
[0m[49m[39m  214, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 218[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  216, 219[0m:[39m[49m CONTEXT_WINDOW_CHARS = 300  // characters before and after the entity
[0m[49m[39m  217, 220[0m:[39m[49m                             // roughly 2-3 sentences of surrounding context
[0m[49m[39m  218, 221[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  219, 222[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_context_windows(note_text, entities):
[0m[49m[39m  220, 223[0m:[39m[49m     // Build a context window around each entity for the assertion classifier.
[0m[49m[39m  221, 224[0m:[39m[49m     // The goal: give the classifier enough text to identify negation cues,
[0m[49m[39m  222, 225[0m:[39m[49m     // hedging language, and section-level context without overwhelming it.
[0m[49m[39m  223, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  224, 227[0m:[39m[49m     entity_contexts = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  225, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  226, 229[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each entity in entities:
[0m[49m[39m  227, 230[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate window boundaries, clamping to document edges
[0m[49m[39m  228, 231[0m:[39m[49m         window_start = max(0, entity.begin_offset - CONTEXT_WINDOW_CHARS)
[0m[49m[39m  229, 232[0m:[39m[49m         window_end   = min(length(note_text), entity.end_offset + CONTEXT_WINDOW_CHARS)
[0m[49m[39m  230, 233[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  231, 234[0m:[39m[49m         // Extract the context text
[0m[49m[39m  232, 235[0m:[39m[49m         context_text = note_text[window_start : window_end]
[0m[49m[39m  233, 236[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  234, 237[0m:[39m[49m         // Calculate where the entity sits within this context window
[0m[49m[39m  235, 238[0m:[39m[49m         // The classifier needs to know which span is "the entity" vs. "the context"
[0m[49m[39m  236, 239[0m:[39m[49m         entity_start_in_context = entity.begin_offset - window_start
[0m[49m[39m  237, 240[0m:[39m[49m         entity_end_in_context   = entity.end_offset - window_start
[0m[49m[39m  238, 241[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 242[0m:[39m[49m         // Attempt to detect the section header for this region of the note.
[0m[49m[39m  240, 243[0m:[39m[49m         // Section headers like "Family History:" or "Assessment:" carry strong
[0m[49m[39m  241, 244[0m:[39m[49m         // assertion signals. If we can't detect one, that's fine; the classifier
[0m[49m[39m  242, 245[0m:[39m[49m         // can still work from the text context alone.
[0m[49m[39m  243, 246[0m:[39m[49m         section_header = detect_section_header(note_text, entity.begin_offset)
[0m[49m[39m  244, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  245, 248[0m:[39m[49m         append to entity_contexts: {
[0m[49m[39m  246, 249[0m:[39m[49m             entity: entity,
[0m[49m[39m  247, 250[0m:[39m[49m             context_text: context_text,
[0m[49m[39m  248, 251[0m:[39m[49m             entity_start_in_context: entity_start_in_context,
[0m[49m[39m  249, 252[0m:[39m[49m             entity_end_in_context: entity_end_in_context,
[0m[49m[39m  250, 253[0m:[39m[49m             section_header: section_header   // may be null if undetectable
[0m[49m[39m  251, 254[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  252, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  253, 256[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN entity_contexts
[0m[49m[39m  254, 257[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  255, 258[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  256, 259[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Classify assertion status.** This is the core step. For each entity in its context window, the assertion classifier predicts the factual status: present, absent, possible, conditional, historical, family, or hypothetical. In our hybrid approach, we first check if simple rules can resolve the assertion (clear negation patterns catch about 60% of absent cases quickly and cheaply). Everything the rules can't confidently classify goes to the ML model. The model input is the context text with the entity span marked using special tokens so the model knows exactly which concept to classify.
[0m[49m[39m  257, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A2 (HIGH). Add two-tier threshold guidance: 0.70 (exclude from downstream until reviewed) and 0.85 (include with low_confidence flag, queue for review). Estimate reviewer time at 20-30s per entity. At 200 entities/day that's ~1.5 hours of reviewer time. Address whether low-confidence entities are included in downstream with caveats or excluded until reviewed. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  258, 263[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  259, 264[0m:[39m[49m // Assertion classes the system can assign
[0m[49m[39m  260, 265[0m:[39m[49m ASSERTION_CLASSES = ["present", "absent", "possible", "conditional",
[0m[49m[39m  261, 266[0m:[39m[49m                      "historical", "family", "hypothetical"]
[0m[49m[39m  262, 267[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  263, 268[0m:[39m[49m // Confidence threshold: below this, flag for human review
[0m[49m[39m  264, 269[0m:[39m[49m CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD = 0.85
[0m[49m[39m  265, 270[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  266, 271[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION classify_assertions(entity_contexts):
[0m[49m[39m  267, 272[0m:[39m[49m     // Two-pass approach: rules first (fast, cheap), then ML model for the rest.
[0m[49m[39m  268, 273[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  269, 274[0m:[39m[49m     results = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  270, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  271, 276[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each ctx in entity_contexts:
[0m[49m[39m  272, 277[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  273, 278[0m:[39m[49m         // === Pass 1: Rule-based negation/section detection ===
[0m[49m[39m  274, 279[0m:[39m[49m         // Fast, deterministic, handles the obvious cases.
[0m[49m[39m  275, 280[0m:[39m[49m         rule_result = apply_assertion_rules(ctx)
[0m[49m[39m  276, 281[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  277, 282[0m:[39m[49m         IF rule_result is not null AND rule_result.confidence >= CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD:
[0m[49m[39m  278, 283[0m:[39m[49m             // Rules handled it confidently. No need to invoke the model.
[0m[49m[39m  279, 284[0m:[39m[49m             append to results: {
[0m[49m[39m  280, 285[0m:[39m[49m                 entity: ctx.entity,
[0m[49m[39m  281, 286[0m:[39m[49m                 assertion: rule_result.assertion,
[0m[49m[39m  282, 287[0m:[39m[49m                 confidence: rule_result.confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  283, 288[0m:[39m[49m                 method: "rule_based"
[0m[49m[39m  284, 289[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  285, 290[0m:[39m[49m             CONTINUE  // next entity
[0m[49m[39m  286, 291[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  287, 292[0m:[39m[49m         // === Pass 2: ML model for ambiguous cases ===
[0m[49m[39m  288, 293[0m:[39m[49m         // Format input: insert [ENTITY] markers around the target span so
[0m[49m[39m  289, 294[0m:[39m[49m         // the model knows which concept to classify.
[0m[49m[39m  290, 295[0m:[39m[49m         // Example: "Patient denies [ENTITY]chest pain[/ENTITY] but reports..."
[0m[49m[39m  291, 296[0m:[39m[49m         model_input = format_model_input(ctx.context_text,
[0m[49m[39m  292, 297[0m:[39m[49m                                          ctx.entity_start_in_context,
[0m[49m[39m  293, 298[0m:[39m[49m                                          ctx.entity_end_in_context,
[0m[49m[39m  294, 299[0m:[39m[49m                                          ctx.section_header)
[0m[49m[39m  295, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  296, 301[0m:[39m[49m         // Call the trained assertion classifier
[0m[49m[39m  297, 302[0m:[39m[49m         prediction = call AssertionModel.predict(model_input)
[0m[49m[39m  298, 303[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 304[0m:[39m[49m         append to results: {
[0m[49m[39m  300, 305[0m:[39m[49m             entity: ctx.entity,
[0m[49m[39m  301, 306[0m:[39m[49m             assertion: prediction.assertion_class,
[0m[49m[39m  302, 307[0m:[39m[49m             confidence: prediction.confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  303, 308[0m:[39m[49m             method: "ml_model"
[0m[49m[39m  304, 309[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  305, 310[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  306, 311[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN results
[0m[49m[39m  307, 312[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  308, 313[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 314[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_assertion_rules(ctx):
[0m[49m[39m  310, 315[0m:[39m[49m     // Simple rule-based assertion detection for high-confidence cases.
[0m[49m[39m  311, 316[0m:[39m[49m     // Catches obvious negations, family history sections, and clear temporal cues.
[0m[49m[39m  312, 317[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 318[0m:[39m[49m     text_before_entity = lowercase(ctx.context_text[0 : ctx.entity_start_in_context])
[0m[49m[39m  314, 319[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  315, 320[0m:[39m[49m     // Check section header first (strongest signal)
[0m[49m[39m  316, 321[0m:[39m[49m     IF ctx.section_header is not null:
[0m[49m[39m  317, 322[0m:[39m[49m         IF ctx.section_header matches ["family history", "fhx", "family hx"]:
[0m[49m[39m  318, 323[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN { assertion: "family", confidence: 0.95 }
[0m[49m[39m  319, 324[0m:[39m[49m         IF ctx.section_header matches ["past medical history", "pmh", "past surgical history"]:
[0m[49m[39m  320, 325[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN { assertion: "historical", confidence: 0.90 }
[0m[49m[39m  321, 326[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  322, 327[0m:[39m[49m     // Check for clear negation cues within scope
[0m[49m[39m  323, 328[0m:[39m[49m     negation_cues = ["no ", "no evidence of", "denies", "denied", "negative for",
[0m[49m[39m  324, 329[0m:[39m[49m                      "without", "rules out", "ruled out", "absence of"]
[0m[49m[39m  325, 330[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  326, 331[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cue in negation_cues:
[0m[49m[39m  327, 332[0m:[39m[49m         IF cue is found in text_before_entity within 60 characters of entity:
[0m[49m[39m  328, 333[0m:[39m[49m             // Check for pseudo-negation patterns that look like negation but aren't
[0m[49m[39m  329, 334[0m:[39m[49m             // Example: "not only" or "no longer" (which implies it WAS present)
[0m[49m[39m  330, 335[0m:[39m[49m             IF NOT contains_pseudo_negation(text_before_entity, cue):
[0m[49m[39m  331, 336[0m:[39m[49m                 RETURN { assertion: "absent", confidence: 0.92 }
[0m[49m[39m  332, 337[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 338[0m:[39m[49m     // Check for historical cues
[0m[49m[39m  334, 339[0m:[39m[49m     historical_cues = ["history of", "h/o", "s/p", "status post", "previously",
[0m[49m[39m  335, 340[0m:[39m[49m                        "prior", "in the past", "resolved"]
[0m[49m[39m  336, 341[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each cue in historical_cues:
[0m[49m[39m  337, 342[0m:[39m[49m         IF cue is found in text_before_entity within 40 characters of entity:
[0m[49m[39m  338, 343[0m:[39m[49m             RETURN { assertion: "historical", confidence: 0.88 }
[0m[49m[39m  339, 344[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  340, 345[0m:[39m[49m     // Rules couldn't confidently classify this one
[0m[49m[39m  341, 346[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN null
[0m[49m[39m  342, 347[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  343, 348[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 344     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 4: Post-process and resolve conflicts.** When the same clinical concept appears multiple times in a note with different assertion statuses, we need to determine the "current truth." This step consolidates multiple mentions into a single assertion per unique concept. The precedence logic: the most recent, most specific mention in the note wins. A concept that is "historical" in Past Medical History but "present" in today's Assessment is currently present. A concept that is "possible" in the initial impression but "absent" in the final assessment (after workup) is absent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Post-process and resolve conflicts.** When the same clinical concept appears multiple times in a note with different assertion statuses, we need to determine the "current truth." This step consolidates multiple mentions into a single assertion per unique concept. The precedence logic uses a default heuristic: the most recent, most specific mention in the note wins. A concept that is "historical" in Past Medical History but "present" in today's Assessment is currently present. A concept that is "possible" in the initial impression but "absent" in the final assessment (after workup) is absent.
[0m[49m[39m  345, 350[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A3 (HIGH). Conflict resolution oversimplifies clinical reality. The section-priority heuristic fails on copy-forward notes, multi-day notes, and cases where both assertions are valid for different clinical questions. Recommend: (1) retain all mentions with individual assertions rather than resolving to a single winner; (2) let downstream consumers specify resolution strategy via a conflict_resolution_strategy parameter; (3) acknowledge the heuristic is a default, not ground truth. Update pseudocode comment from "Pick the highest-priority one" to note this is a default heuristic. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  346, 353[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  347, 354[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION resolve_assertion_conflicts(classified_entities):
[0m[49m[39m  348, 355[0m:[39m[49m     // Group mentions of the same clinical concept and resolve to a single assertion.
[0m[49m[39m  349, 356[0m:[39m[49m     // This handles the common case where "diabetes" appears in PMH (historical)
[0m[49m[39m  350, 357[0m:[39m[49m     // AND in Assessment (present). The most clinically relevant assertion wins.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     //
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // NOTE: This section-priority approach is a default heuristic, not ground truth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // It handles the common case (Assessment reflects current clinical state) but
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // fails on copy-forward notes, multi-day notes, and situations where both
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // assertions are valid for different clinical questions. Production systems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // should retain all mentions and let downstream consumers choose their
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // resolution strategy.
[0m[49m[39m  351, 365[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  352, 366[0m:[39m[49m     // Precedence order (later in note + more specific = higher priority):
[0m[49m[39m  353, 367[0m:[39m[49m     // Assessment/Plan > HPI > Review of Systems > Past Medical History > Family History
[0m[49m[39m  354, 368[0m:[39m[49m     SECTION_PRIORITY = {
[0m[49m[39m  355, 369[0m:[39m[49m         "assessment": 5, "plan": 5, "a/p": 5,
[0m[49m[39m  356, 370[0m:[39m[49m         "hpi": 4, "history of present illness": 4,
[0m[49m[39m  357, 371[0m:[39m[49m         "ros": 3, "review of systems": 3,
[0m[49m[39m  358, 372[0m:[39m[49m         "pmh": 2, "past medical history": 2,
[0m[49m[39m  359, 373[0m:[39m[49m         "fhx": 1, "family history": 1
[0m[49m[39m  360, 374[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  361, 375[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  362, 376[0m:[39m[49m     // Group entities by normalized text (same concept, different mentions)
[0m[49m[39m  363, 377[0m:[39m[49m     concept_groups = group classified_entities by normalized entity text
[0m[49m[39m  364, 378[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  365, 379[0m:[39m[49m     resolved = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  366, 380[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  367, 381[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each concept, mentions in concept_groups:
[0m[49m[39m  368, 382[0m:[39m[49m         IF length(mentions) == 1:
[0m[49m[39m  369, 383[0m:[39m[49m             // Only one mention. No conflict to resolve.
[0m[49m[39m  370, 384[0m:[39m[49m             append to resolved: mentions[0]
[0m[49m[39m  371, 385[0m:[39m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 372     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m             // Multiple mentions. Pick the highest-priority one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Multiple mentions. Use section priority as a default heuristic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // (Break ties by position in note: later = higher priority.)
[0m[49m[39m  373, 388[0m:[39m[49m             best = select mention with highest section priority
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 374     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m                    (break ties by position in note: later = higher priority)
[0m[49m[39m  375, 389[0m:[39m[49m             // Keep all mentions for audit, but mark the resolved assertion
[0m[49m[39m  376, 390[0m:[39m[49m             append to resolved: {
[0m[49m[39m  377, 391[0m:[39m[49m                 entity: best.entity,
[0m[49m[39m  378, 392[0m:[39m[49m                 assertion: best.assertion,
[0m[49m[39m  379, 393[0m:[39m[49m                 confidence: best.confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  380, 394[0m:[39m[49m                 method: best.method,
[0m[49m[39m  381, 395[0m:[39m[49m                 all_mentions: mentions,   // full audit trail
[0m[49m[39m  382, 396[0m:[39m[49m                 conflict_resolved: true
[0m[49m[39m  383, 397[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  384, 398[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  385, 399[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN resolved
[0m[49m[39m  386, 400[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  387, 401[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  388, 402[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store annotated entities.** Write the final assertion-classified entities to the database. Each record connects back to the source note, includes the full entity context for audit, and is indexed by patient, date, entity type, and assertion status. Downstream systems query this store to answer questions like "what conditions are currently present for this patient?" or "which patients have a family history of breast cancer?"
[0m[49m[39m  389, 403[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (HIGH). Add DynamoDB TTL on a ttl_epoch attribute aligned with institutional records retention policy (typically 7-10 years). Document that context_snippet should live in a separate restricted-access audit table (finding S2, MEDIUM), and that the needs_review queue requires role-based access control and audit logging of reviewer actions (finding S3, MEDIUM). -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  390, 406[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  391, 407[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_annotated_entities(patient_id, note_id, note_date, resolved_entities):
[0m[49m[39m  392, 408[0m:[39m[49m     // Write each assertion-annotated entity to the database.
[0m[49m[39m  393, 409[0m:[39m[49m     // Index by patient + assertion status for fast downstream queries.
[0m[49m[39m  394, 410[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  395, 411[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each result in resolved_entities:
[0m[49m[39m  396, 412[0m:[39m[49m         write record to database table "assertion-annotated-entities":
[0m[49m[39m  397, 413[0m:[39m[49m             patient_id       = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  398, 414[0m:[39m[49m             note_id          = note_id
[0m[49m[39m  399, 415[0m:[39m[49m             note_date        = note_date
[0m[49m[39m  400, 416[0m:[39m[49m             entity_text      = result.entity.text
[0m[49m[39m  401, 417[0m:[39m[49m             entity_category  = result.entity.category
[0m[49m[39m  402, 418[0m:[39m[49m             assertion_status = result.assertion           // present, absent, possible, etc.
[0m[49m[39m  403, 419[0m:[39m[49m             confidence       = result.confidence
[0m[49m[39m  404, 420[0m:[39m[49m             method           = result.method             // rule_based or ml_model
[0m[49m[39m  405, 421[0m:[39m[49m             needs_review     = (result.confidence < CONFIDENCE_THRESHOLD)
[0m[49m[39m  406, 422[0m:[39m[49m             context_snippet  = result.entity.context_text[relevant portion]
[0m[49m[39m  407, 423[0m:[39m[49m             processed_at     = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[39m  408, 424[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  409, 425[0m:[39m[49m     // Also write a summary record for the note showing assertion distribution
[0m[49m[39m  410, 426[0m:[39m[49m     write summary to database table "note-assertion-summary":
[0m[49m[39m  411, 427[0m:[39m[49m         note_id     = note_id
[0m[49m[39m  412, 428[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id  = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  413, 429[0m:[39m[49m         note_date   = note_date
[0m[49m[39m  414, 430[0m:[39m[49m         total_entities   = count of resolved_entities
[0m[49m[39m  415, 431[0m:[39m[49m         present_count    = count where assertion == "present"
[0m[49m[39m  416, 432[0m:[39m[49m         absent_count     = count where assertion == "absent"
[0m[49m[39m  417, 433[0m:[39m[49m         possible_count   = count where assertion == "possible"
[0m[49m[39m  418, 434[0m:[39m[49m         historical_count = count where assertion == "historical"
[0m[49m[39m  419, 435[0m:[39m[49m         family_count     = count where assertion == "family"
[0m[49m[39m  420, 436[0m:[39m[49m         review_needed    = count where needs_review == true
[0m[49m[39m  421, 437[0m:[39m[49m ```
